>
  <p>
    Outdoor storage is often most noticeable from inside the house. A cushion box replaces the
    garden view, toys gather beside it and barbecue tools migrate to the garage because the box
    is awkward to open once the chairs are out.
  </p>
  <p>
    Notice what is left outside after use and why. Some things need quick access; others need
    protection from sun, rain, dust or wind. Keep the main purpose of the patio, balcony or garden
    in charge, then fit storage around movement, seating and the conditions at that exact spot.
  </p>

  <section aria-labelledby="outdoor-storage-plan-heading">
    <h2 id="outdoor-storage-plan-heading">Choose outdoor storage in this order</h2>
    <ol class="numbered-list">
      <li>Remove anything that does not genuinely need to live outside.</li>
      <li>Protect the door, seating area, balcony or garden path before assigning floor space.</li>
      <li>Match the box, bench or cabinet to the rain, sun, wind and drainage at that spot.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Only then compare capacity. A larger unit is not useful if it makes the outdoor area harder to use.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2>Sort by exposure as well as frequency</h2>
  <p>
    Begin with what genuinely needs to live outdoors. Garden tools and a hose may need to stay
    close to the yard. Cushions, beach gear or entertaining supplies might be safer and drier
    inside when they are not in use.
  </p>
  <p>Divide what remains into three groups:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Everyday items that need one-step access.</li>
    <li>Occasional items that can sit in deeper or closed storage.</li>
    <li>Sensitive, hazardous or valuable items that need a more suitable location.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If the area is especially tight, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-storage-for-small-australian-backyards-what-to-plan-before-buying/">small outdoor storage guide</a>{" "}
    goes further into boxes, cabinets, sheds, access and exposure.
  </p>

  <h2>Map the outdoor room before adding a box</h2>
  <p>
    Measure the storage footprint with its lid or doors fully open. Protect the route from the
    house, the space needed to pull out a chair and access to taps, drains, railings and garden
    beds. On a balcony, check rental or body corporate requirements and any limits relevant to
    the space before adding large items or wall fixings.
  </p>
  <p>
    Storage should also leave room for the activity already planned there. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-dining-area-setup-what-to-measure-before-buying-furniture/">outdoor dining guide</a>{" "}
    covers chair clearance and serving routes, while the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-lounge-area-setup-what-to-measure-before-buying-seating/">outdoor lounge guide</a>{" "}
    focuses on seating depth and movement.
  </p>

  <figure class="article-figure">
    <img
      src="/images/guides/outdoor-storage-brick-courtyard.webp"
      alt="A brick townhouse courtyard with an open garden cabinet, upright tool rack and clear path from the back door"
      width="1440"
      height="960"
      loading="lazy"
      decoding="async"
    />
