      AI-generated illustrative example, not a photographed project. The cabinet opens onto empty
      paving while the tools and hose stay outside the route from the back door; check your own
      dimensions, exposure and building requirements.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>Match the storage claim to the actual weather</h2>
  <p>
    “Outdoor”, “weather-resistant” and “waterproof” do not necessarily promise the same level of
    protection. Read the product information and consider whether the location receives driving
    rain, intense afternoon sun, salt air, dust or water pooling beneath it.
  </p>
  <p>
    Plastic or resin can be light and easy to clean, but quality and UV resistance matter. Coated
    metal may offer strength, though damaged coatings and coastal exposure can encourage
    corrosion. Timber can suit the garden visually but may need ongoing maintenance. Choose for
    the exposed position, not just the material name.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep cushions dry enough to store</h2>
  <p>
    Even outdoor-rated cushions benefit from protection when they are not being used. A box,
    bench, bag or cupboard may work, provided the cushions fit without being forced and the
    storage remains dry and ventilated as its instructions require.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not seal damp cushions away. Let them dry first, particularly in humid or coastal areas
    where trapped moisture can lead to odour or mildew. If the available box cannot hold the
    cushion set comfortably, fewer cushions may be a better answer than larger storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Make a storage bench pass both tests</h2>
  <p>
    A bench can combine seating and storage on a small patio, but only if it works in both roles.
    Check seat height and stability, lid clearance, internal dimensions and whether the contents
    will be crushed when people sit down. Confirm that the product is designed to be used as
    seating rather than assuming any storage box can take a person's weight.
  </p>
  <p>
    Place it where the lid can open without moving the dining table or blocking the door. A
    dual-purpose product that needs the whole area rearranged each time is not saving useful
    space.
  </p>

  <h2>Store tools where they cannot fall into the path</h2>
  <p>
    Long-handled tools are easier to manage when they stand in a stable rack or hang from a
    suitable fixing rather than lean against a wall. Keep frequently used tools within easy reach
    and store heavy items lower down. A small caddy can hold gloves, secateurs and hand tools close
    to the garden task.
  </p>
  <p>
    Wall-mounted systems depend on the wall, fixings, rated load and installation instructions.
    Renters may need a freestanding stand instead. Protect tools from ongoing rain and clean or
    dry them before storage rather than enclosing soil and moisture.
  </p>

  <h2>Give barbecue gear a clean boundary</h2>
  <p>
    Tongs, trays, covers and cleaning brushes are easier to use when they live near the barbecue,
    but food-related equipment should not share a mixed tub with fertilisers, pest products or
    garden chemicals. A small caddy or dedicated shelf may be enough.
  </p>
  <p>
    Follow the barbecue and gas-cylinder instructions for use and storage, as well as applicable
    local requirements. Do not improvise an enclosed storage position for fuel or heat-producing
    equipment. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/barbecue-area-setup-what-to-measure-before-buying-outdoor-cooking-gear/">barbecue area guide</a>{" "}
    covers the cooking footprint, preparation space and outdoor dining flow.
  </p>

  <h2>Get hoses and cords off the walkway</h2>
  <p>
    A reel or holder can keep a hose accessible without leaving loops across the path. Choose one
    that suits the hose length, wall or ground position and the person who will rewind it. On a
    small balcony, a watering can may be more proportionate than a permanent hose setup.
  </p>
  <p>
    Outdoor electrical leads and lighting need products and connections suitable for their use.
    Keep cords away from water and walkways and follow the equipment instructions rather than
    treating a storage hook as an electrical-safety solution.
  </p>

  <h2>Let wet toys drain before they disappear</h2>
  <p>
    Children's outdoor toys need a return point that is low, stable and simple to use. Open tubs,
    mesh bags and rinseable baskets can work well for sandy or wet items because the contents can
    dry before longer-term storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid turning a deep box into an unsorted toy pit. Keep the frequently used set outside and
    rotate the rest. Check that lids and hinges are suitable for the household and that stored
    water cannot collect in toys or containers.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep pet gear close to the door</h2>
  <p>
    A washable basket or hook near the back door can hold leads, outdoor toys and a dedicated
    towel. It should support the transition inside rather than create a new obstacle on the patio.
  </p>
  <p>
    Store pet food and treats according to the packaging instructions; a hot or damp outdoor box
    may be unsuitable even when it closes securely. Move food, medicines and grooming products to
    a more controlled location where necessary.
  </p>

  <h2>Use shelves only where the contents suit the location</h2>
  <p>
    Shelving can keep pots, watering fittings and small tools off a shed floor, but open shelves
    do not protect against dust, pests or rain. Check shelf load ratings, keep heavier items low
    and avoid placing hazardous products where children or pets can reach them.
  </p>
  <p>
    Clear tubs and labels can help with occasional supplies, provided everything is dry before it
    is enclosed. Pots and planters create their own questions about drainage and floor loading;
    the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/balcony-and-courtyard-garden-setup-what-to-plan-before-buying-pots-and-planters/">balcony and courtyard garden guide</a>{" "}
    covers that setup.
  </p>

  <h2>Leave enough room to clean around storage</h2>
  <p>
    Leaves, dust, webs and pollen collect behind boxes and beneath cabinets. Check whether the
    unit can be moved, whether water drains beneath it and whether the back and hinges are
    reachable. A neat-looking cabinet that traps damp debris against a wall can create more work
    than it removes.
  </p>
  <p>
    Shade changes exposure but also changes the furniture footprint. If an umbrella, gazebo or
    screen is part of the area, place it before committing the remaining wall or floor space to
    storage. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/outdoor-shade-setup-for-patios-and-backyards-what-to-check-before-buying/">outdoor shade guide</a>{" "}
    helps map that zone.
  </p>

  <h2>Before another box or cabinet goes outside</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Name the items it will hold and check they suit the location.</li>
    <li>Measure access with the storage, furniture and doors all in use.</li>
    <li>Compare the product's protection claims with the site's real exposure.</li>
    <li>Check stability, drainage, cleaning access and any installation requirements.</li>
    <li>Keep hazardous products and fuel-related equipment in appropriate, controlled storage.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Outdoor storage has done its job when the area is easier to use and the garden, balcony or
    patio still feels like a place to spend time. Protect the things that need to remain outside,
    move the rest to a more suitable home and resist letting household overflow become the main
    outdoor feature.
  </p>

